.TH ELEV 5 "2026-04-20" "1.0.0" "elev Configuration Manual"
.SH NAME
/etc/elev/conf \- configuration file for elev
.SH DESCRIPTION
The \fB/etc/elev/conf\fR file defines the security policies for the \fBelev\fR(1) utility. It determines which users are allowed to execute commands as other users and under what conditions.

.SH SECURITY REQUIREMENTS
To prevent unauthorized access, \fBelev\fR enforces strict security checks on the configuration file:
.IP \(bu 3
The file must be owned by \fBroot\fR.
.IP \(bu 3
The file must not be writable by group or others (recommended permissions: \fB0600\fR or \fB0644\fR).
.IP \(bu 3
The directory containing the file (\fB/etc/elev/\fR) must also be owned by \fBroot\fR and not writable by others.

.SH SYNTAX
The file consists of rules, one per line. Empty lines and lines starting with \fB#\fR or \fB//\fR are ignored.
Rules are processed from top to bottom. The \fBlast\fR matching rule determines whether the action is permitted or denied.
Invalid configuration lines are fatal; \fBelev\fR rejects the whole file rather
than ignoring malformed rules.

The general format of a rule is:
.IP
[\fBpermit\fR|\fBdeny\fR] [\fIoptions\fR] \fIuser\fR \fBas\fR \fItarget\fR [\fBcmd\fR \fIcommand\fR [\fIargs\fR]]
.PP

.SS Rule Types
.TP
\fBpermit\fR
Allows the execution if all matchers in the rule are met.
.TP
\fBdeny\fR
Explicitly forbids the execution.

.SS Options
Options modify the behavior of a \fBpermit\fR rule.
.TP
\fBnopass\fR
Do not prompt the user for a password. Authentication is automatically considered successful.
.TP
\fBpersist\fR[\fB=\fR\fIduration\fR]
Enable authentication caching. After a successful login, the user won't be prompted for a password for the specified \fIduration\fR.
Units: \fBm\fR (minutes), \fBh\fR (hours), \fBd\fR (days). Example: \fBpersist=15m\fR.
If no duration is specified, a default internal value is used.
Cached credentials are only trusted when the timestamp file lives in a
root-owned runtime directory that is not writable by group or others.
Each timestamp is scoped to the invoking user, TTY, target user, matched rule,
and command line, so one cached authentication does not unlock unrelated
\fBpersist\fR rules.
For non-TTY invocations, persistence is disabled entirely to avoid sharing a
single cache across unrelated background sessions.
The default runtime directory is \fB/var/run/elev\fR, but distributors may
override it at build time.
.TP
\fBkeepenv {\fR\fIVARS\fR\fB}\fR
Allows preserving specific environment variables from the user's session. \fIVARS\fR is a comma-separated list.
Note: Certain dangerous variables (like \fBLD_PRELOAD\fR) are always stripped regardless of this setting.

.SS Matchers
.TP
\fIuser\fR
Specifies the user invoking \fBelev\fR. Can be a \fBusername\fR, a \fB:groupname\fR (prefixed with a colon), or \fB*\fR to match any user.
.TP
\fBas\fR \fItarget\fR
Specifies the user as whom the command will be run. Use \fB*\fR to allow running as any user.
.TP
\fBcmd\fR \fIcommand\fR [\fIargs\fR]
Restrict the rule to a specific absolute path of a command.
If \fIargs\fR are provided, \fBelev\fR performs strict argument matching. You can specify multiple allowed values for an argument using commas (e.g., \fBcmd /bin/ls /tmp,/home\fR).
.TP
\fBdenycmd\fR \fIcommand\fR
An alternative way to explicitly block a specific command path.
This is a policy convenience, not a sandbox or shell escape barrier.

.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
\fBpermit :wheel as root\fR
Allow anyone in the \fBwheel\fR group to run any command as root.
.TP
\fBpermit persist=1h user1 as *\fR
Allow \fBuser1\fR to run as any user, caching their password for 1 hour.
.TP
\fBpermit nopass user2 as root cmd /usr/bin/apt update\fR
Allow \fBuser2\fR to run only \fBapt update\fR as root without a password.

.SH FILES
.I /etc/elev/conf
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR elev (1),
.BR elev (7)
